{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_0","type":"agent_message","text":"**Topology Summary**\n\nUse a flat, single-supply, stacked NMOS Gilbert cell mixer. The bottom NMOS RF differential pair converts `Vrfp - Vrfn` into differential currents at `rf_drp` and `rf_drn`. The upper NMOS LO switching quad steers those RF currents into either `Voutp` or `Voutn` depending on `Vlop - Vlon`. Two `10 kOhm` resistive loads from `VDD = 5 V` to `Voutp` and `Voutn` convert the commutated currents into a differential output voltage.\n\nExpected behavior:\n\n`Voutp - Voutn ∝ (Vrfp - Vrfn) × (Vlop - Vlon)`\n\nWith nominal 1 kHz RF and 1.2 kHz LO drives, transient analysis should show differential tones near `200 Hz` and `2.2 kHz`.\n\n**Device/Function List**\n\n- `Mtail`: NMOS tail current source\n  - Drain: `rf_tail`\n  - Source: `tail_src`\n  - Gate: `Vbias_tail`\n  - Bulk: `tail_src`\n  - `tail_src` should be tied to ground or used as the grounded source node.\n\n- `Mrfp`: RF positive input transconductor\n  - Gate: `Vrfp`\n  - Drain: `rf_drp`\n  - Source/bulk: `rf_tail`\n\n- `Mrfn`: RF negative input transconductor\n  - Gate: `Vrfn`\n  - Drain: `rf_drn`\n  - Source/bulk: `rf_tail`\n\n- `Mlo1`: LO switch steering `rf_drp` current to `Voutp`\n  - Drain: `Voutp`\n  - Source/bulk: `rf_drp`\n  - Gate: `Vlop`\n\n- `Mlo2`: LO switch steering `rf_drp` current to `Voutn`\n  - Drain: `Voutn`\n  - Source/bulk: `rf_drp`\n  - Gate: `Vlon`\n\n- `Mlo3`: LO switch steering `rf_drn` current to `Voutn`\n  - Drain: `Voutn`\n  - Source/bulk: `rf_drn`\n  - Gate: `Vlop`\n\n- `Mlo4`: LO switch steering `rf_drn` current to `Voutp`\n  - Drain: `Voutp`\n  - Source/bulk: `rf_drn`\n  - Gate: `Vlon`\n\n- `Rloadp`: `10 kOhm` from `VDD` to `Voutp`\n- `Rloadn`: `10 kOhm` from `VDD` to `Voutn`\n\n**Bias/Reference Strategy**\n\nUse `VDD = 5 V`.\n\nBias the RF input sources around approximately `2.0 V` common mode with small opposite-phase 1 kHz signals. This keeps the RF pair on without overdriving the stacked devices.\n\nBias the LO inputs around a common mode high enough to switch the upper quad, likely around `3 V` to `4 V`, with opposite-phase 1.2 kHz signals. The LO amplitude should be large enough to alternate conduction between the cross-coupled switch pairs.\n\nSet `Vbias_tail` around `1.1 V` to `1.3 V` for the given NMOS model:\n\n`.model NMOS NMOS (VTO=0.7 KP=100u)`\n\nThis should create moderate tail current while avoiding output saturation. With `10 kOhm` loads, choose the tail current so `Voutp` and `Voutn` sit near mid-supply, not pinned to `5 V` or ground.\n\nTie every NMOS bulk to its local source node as specified.\n\n**Signal or Feedback Path**\n\nThere is no stabilizing feedback loop. This is an open-loop switching transconductance mixer.\n\nSignal flow:\n\n`Vrfp - Vrfn` drives the lower differential pair, producing opposite drain currents at `rf_drp` and `rf_drn`.\n\n`Vlop - Vlon` drives the upper quad, commutating those RF currents into `Voutp` and `Voutn`.\n\nThe resistive loads convert current steering into voltage swings. The cross-connected LO devices invert the output polarity on alternate LO phases, creating the multiplication action.\n\n**SPICE/Netlist Constraints**\n\nThe final file should be named `p19.cir`.\n\nThe final netlist must be flat: no subcircuits, no behavioral multiplier, no hidden controlled-source shortcut.\n\nRequired exact external node names:\n\n- Inputs: `Vrfp`, `Vrfn`, `Vlop`, `Vlon`\n- Outputs: `Voutp`, `Voutn`\n\nThe netlist must include independent voltage sources explicitly connected to `Vrfp`, `Vrfn`, `Vlop`, and `Vlon`, even if the checker later replaces them.\n\nInclude:\n\n- `VDD` source fixed at `5 V`\n- `Vbias_tail` source\n- Two `10 kOhm` loads\n- NMOS model with `Vth/VTO = 0.7 V`, `KP = 100u`, `W = 50u`, `L = 1u`\n- `.tran 1u 5m`\n\n**Failure Risks To Avoid**\n\n- Do not omit explicit RF/LO voltage sources; the checker expects the ports to exist.\n- Do not rename ports. Preserve `Vrfp`, `Vrfn`, `Vlop`, `Vlon`, `Voutp`, `Voutn` exactly.\n- Do not accidentally connect the LO quad in a non-crossed pattern; wrong commutation polarity will suppress the desired differential product.\n- Do not let `Voutp` and `Voutn` rail at `VDD` from too little current or collapse near ground from too much tail current.\n- Do not choose LO common mode too low; the upper NMOS switches need enough gate voltage above `rf_drp/rf_drn`.\n- Do not leave NMOS bulks floating or tied globally to ground when the spec requires source-tied bulks.\n- Do not use PMOS loads, active loads, subcircuits, or behavioral multiplication; the requested topology is resistively loaded NMOS Gilbert cell."}}
